text_retweet:
please repost or tag someone you think would be interested - the more people who see this, the better (link in profile):
"the national sexual assault online hotline, operated by @rainn, provides live, secure, anonymous crisis support to the growing number of people who prefer communicating online through a simple instant message format, giving those affected by sexual assault a safe place to receive support." as a new volunteer, i can say that receiving this training and working on the hotline has changed *my* life. not only am i able to make a difference for those in crisis, but it's boosted my knowledge and ability to this work in this space. and i'm as humbled by the experience as i am impressed by the expertise, dedication, and support from the people who lead this resource. the training gave me information and skills i could never have developed elsewhere, and they're applicable in so many areas of my life, not just when i'm actually working a shift. the training is extremely intensive, and the commitment (10 hours a month for 18 months) is realistic even in my busy life. 
i never thought i could do something like this - but the training changed everything. if you have questions, please feel free to ask. and even if it's not something you feel is right for you, please help me spread the word. âœ’ğŸ–¤
@thewordforthis

text:
a shout out to single moms. i am a â€œstatisticâ€. i was raised by single mom. i am a single mom. we are bad ass mo-fukâ€™n women. 
this year, iâ€™ve been working hard at â€œacceptingâ€ my â€œsituationâ€ (so itâ€™s been called), including changing the language to â€œthis is #myfamily â€. this is the hardest job iâ€™ve ever had in my life. i didnâ€™t plan on raising a family by myself. i spent my fair share of days crying, or feeling guilty for not feeling enough. iâ€™ve felt ashamed to tell people my truth about my family. iâ€™ve had men who are coupled up specifically stay away from because they donâ€™t want their wives to think iâ€™m hitting on them. iâ€™ve had people not wanting to get together with me and my kids because i donâ€™t have someone to entertain their husband (a significant other). iâ€™ve been afraid to tell potential employers in the past that i am a single parent, concerned they would evaluate me based off of my personal life. iâ€™ve had people ask me â€œwhat does your husband doâ€, and have just lied because i donâ€™t want to be reminded that day that i am alone. 
in 2018, i made a choice to be alone, and to walk away from an abusive relationship. i am thankful everyday for the people who helped me do this- it was hard. my biggest insecurity of being a single parent is what kept me there for so long, hence why i am paying homage to the single parents of this world whether it was a choice, or not. 
being a mom with a partner can already be a lonely job. being a single mom is even lonelier. so cheers to the fucking single moms/dads who get up every day and feed your kids, and cheers to the single moms/dads who take their kids to the park or anywhere else really, and cheers to single moms/dads who can place their life issues aside and still give their kids the time of their lives, and cheers to this fucking stigma because it just isnâ€™t relevant anymore! 
thank you to everyone who has accepted us, for us and who are helping me raise these fantastic boys of mine. iâ€™m so fortunate to have been handed such loving humans to call my own who grab life by the balls/ovaries and just givâ€™r 
#singlemom #singleparent #ittakesavillage #momofboys #carryon #metoo

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon

text:
according to the times, cambridge analytica bought the data from aleksandr kogan, a russian-american academic. kogan, who told facebook he was conducting academic research, built a facebook personality quiz app called "thisisyourdigitalife." when users downloaded the app, it scraped all of their available facebook data, including their friends, their likes and where they lived.

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

more than a quarter-million facebook users downloaded the app, which also exploited a facebook vulnerability that allowed it to to collect most of the same data from the friends of those who downloaded it. by prying into the friends lists of those who made the download, kogan was able to get data from more than 50 million people.

throughout 2015 and into 2016, the cruz campaign paid cambridge analytica almost $6 million for data that the campaign used for what it called "psychographic targeting," which supposedly allowed the campaign to tailor its message to specific voters in places like iowa and new hampshire, where single voters can make a big difference. using data from the firm, the campaign built profiles of potential voters, prioritizing those who fit in categories such as "stoic traditionalist" and "true believer". in december 2015, the same month the guardian revealed cambridge analytica and kogan's data harvesting practices, cruz campaign spokesman rick tyler called the company a "market leader and the best in the field." despite tyler's claim that the cruz campaign stopped using the firm's data in early 2016, it kept paying cambridge analytica until june of that year, a month after cruz suspended his campaign. after cruz dropped out of the race, the firm began working with trump, supporting him through november's general election against hillary clinton.

stephen young
dallas observer

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
as a survivor of sexual assault, my healing comes in waves. there are months where i feel strong and empowered - where i want to take on the world and show my grit and determination to thrive, despite the evil that has existed in my world. but then the months come where i am drained, exhausted, and filled with self hatred. in these dark times, healing seems distant. i feel an overwhelming sense of unworthiness. that no one could ever love the broken parts of me. that itâ€™s all for naught. i do not feel strong. i do not feel brave. and finding the will to even exist becomes my greatest struggle. and these thoughts consume me, day in and day out. and it hurts. and it makes me angry.

however, on my journey to self love - i decided to tape this to my bathroom mirror a few months ago so that i am reminded daily that i must be compassionate toward myself. i deserve love, peace and rest, joy, and so much more. if i do not give myself these things - then my abuser wins. and i no longer can give him that kind of power over my life. ğŸŒ»ğŸŒ»ğŸŒ» wonâ€™t you join me, my sisters, in this journey of radical self love and acceptance? â€¢

sgbv training on 9/2/2019 (sat) 
our heartfelt thanks to organizers (mewro), melisa and team from women aid organization (wao) malaysia, hui ying tham the director of asylum access malaysia, cherryn certe (co-ordinator, mewro) secretary of fro sponsored for lunch and refreshment, the place is accommodated by malaysia karen organization,  the participants, ruth education center (rec) , kachin refugee committee, alliance of chin refugees, chin refugees committee,  arakan refugee relief committee,  zomi refugee committe,  zomi associations of malaysia, mon refugee organization, shan refugee organization, dai community, malaysia karen organization.

we believe empower women is empower society. to break the chain of violence,  we need to educate our society.

participants feedbacks 
from todayâ€™sâ€™ lesson called â€œsgbvâ€ i discovered that it is not the fault of those who dress up very uncomfortably when they go out or anywhere but it is the fault of those who look at them insecurely. yet, it doesnâ€™t mean we are allowed to wear whatever we want, we should be aware and that we should dress up comfortably and securely. and another thing i was reminded is that women and man are equal ; the characters and qualities are almost all the same. therefore, women too have the same right as man.
from jenny:. i learned much from this training. one lesson is about how to help in a crisis. the people who help out in those 
situations are called pfa which stands for psychological first aid ( first thing that happens after an accident(. pfa can be done by anyone.
let's say,  unfortunately there is an earthquake. from that fact the survivors will need help in terms of physical (eg.food,water etc.), mental & emotional (fear, worried ect.), social & economic ( house,land ect.) in order to help the people the pfa needs to have good communication.
there are three steps look, listen, link. firstly, look-we need to be calm & 
show understanding, our body languague & eye contact are

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
watch the trailer for new #metoo film â€˜rocking the couchâ€™
#
one of the most important releases of the year, rocking the couch, available on demand this february from avail films.hollywood titans, harvey weinstein and bill cosby, have been brought to their knees by the #metoo movement. but they did not invent casting couch. the term casting couch has existed for decades. but in 1992, a case against talent agent, wallace kaye, was brought to court by 12 unknown actresses, who braved the loss of their careers, their privacy, and their hollywood dreams. they stepped forward, despite the advice of their union, and brought the case to the police. against all odds, they won, and no one listened.our documentary explores the case and asks, "why didn't we hear about this?" more importantly, why didn't hollywood learn from this case? for, if they had, maybe the cosbys and the weinsteins would have learned as well, and these sexual exploitations could have been prevented."those who ignore history are bound to repeat it."from writer/director minh collins, produced by andrea evans, minh collins, and jerry sommer, and starring lauren anastasi-peter, ikon barenbolm, alana crow, jennifer durst, andrea evans, tiffani fest and sadie katz, rocking the couch is now available on amazon u.s and uk. watchâ€¦

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

text:
shout out to my dear sister friend marcia pendelton of walk tall girl productions for the chance to check out "the light" by loy a. webb at mcc theater. bravo to @mandimasden and @mckinleybcubed who deliver stunning performances while unpacking the complexities of black love --- and masculinity and femininity ...in these polarizing times of #metoo, #timesup,  #muterkelly,  and #kavanaugh. you must see the light by loy a. webb. directed by logan vaughn. now thru march 17 at mcc theater, 511 w. 52nd street, nyc. tickets $45/$75 with code mccwtgp (reg $69/$99) for tickets and more info visit www.mcctheater.org #lifeofriley 
p.s. hill harper and carl nelson were in the house!
p.p.s. look for more on the light with an upcoming d. briggs media look at nyc theater 2019.

shout out to my dear sister friend marcia pendelton of walk tall girl productions for the chance to check out "the light" by loy a. webb at mcc theater. bravo to @mandimasden and @mckinleybcubed who deliver stunning performances while unpacking the complexities of black love --- and masculinity and femininity ...in these polarizing times of #metoo, #timesup,  #muterkelly,  and #kavanaugh. you must see the light by loy a. webb. directed by logan vaughn. now thru march 17 at mcc theater, 511 w. 52nd street, nyc. tickets $45/$75 with code mccwtgp (reg $69/$99) for tickets and more info visit www.mcctheater.org #lifeofriley 
p.s. hill harper and carl nelson were in the house!
p.p.s. look for more on the light with an upcoming d. briggs media look at nyc theater 2019.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

time to ask yourself what you really want...

â€œiâ€™m 15 years old and iâ€™m a victim of sexual assault.â€ those words pierced my heart. a teenage girl uttered them just seconds after a male teenager announced he came out to his parents.  i honestly didnâ€™t know how to react until i heard the thunderous applause from everyone around me at the fiorello h. laguardia high school 2019 rising stars this is me: a journey talent show. 
it takes courage to stand in front of a group of strangers and make these admissions, i thought. 
iâ€™d come to the show at the urging of my mentee, emily. i didnâ€™t feel like going by the time 6 oâ€™clock rolled around. yet, i said good night to the writer iâ€™d been training for half the week and headed to dinner with emily.

after we caught up, we fought the wind coming off the hudson river on manhattanâ€™s upper west side to make it back to her school just in time for the start of the show.

there were familiar tunes like, â€œbeautifulâ€ â€œmy funny valentine,â€ â€œunpretty,â€ â€œhuddled massesâ€ and â€œout here on my own.â€ but, the original song â€œthe outspoken truth,â€ spoke me. it boldly outlined injustices and inequality in our society while celebrating uniqueness, bravery and strength. it helped me see that we should all use our talents to entertain, as well as share our truth, hopes and aspirations without shame, fear of rejection, judgement, and persecution.

text:
your abusive partner doesnâ€™t have a problem with his anger; he has a problem with your anger.one of the basic human rights he takes away from you is the right to be angry with him. no matter how badly he treats you, he believes that your voice shouldnâ€™t rise and your blood shouldnâ€™t boil. the privilege of rage is reserved for him alone. when your anger does jump out of youâ€”as will happen to any abused woman from time to timeâ€”he is likely to try to jam it back down your throat as quickly as he can. then he uses your anger against you to prove what an irrational person you are. abuse can make you feel straitjacketed. you may develop physical or emotional reactions to swallowing your anger, such as depression, nightmares, emotional numbing, or eating and sleeping problems, which your partner may use as an excuse to belittle you further or make you feel crazy. .

your abusive partner doesnâ€™t have a problem with his anger; he has a problem with your anger.one of the basic human rights he takes away from you is the right to be angry with him. no matter how badly he treats you, he believes that your voice shouldnâ€™t rise and your blood shouldnâ€™t boil. the privilege of rage is reserved for him alone. when your anger does jump out of youâ€”as will happen to any abused woman from time to timeâ€”he is likely to try to jam it back down your throat as quickly as he can. then he uses your anger against you to prove what an irrational person you are. abuse can make you feel straitjacketed. you may develop physical or emotional reactions to swallowing your anger, such as depression, nightmares, emotional numbing, or eating and sleeping problems, which your partner may use as an excuse to belittle you further or make you feel crazy. .
.
.

text_retweet:
#repost with @repostlyapp @earthlove777 rp @meat_your_future 
the miracle of life is torture for dairy cows, as their babies are taken from them again and again.
.
like any mammal, cows only produce milk for their calves, after they delivered a baby calf. but because we want their milk, we forcibly impregnate them over and over, to get and keep them lactating, and take their calves away after they are born.  this obviously causes intense distress for both the mother and her baby.
.
the surplus calves (including all of the males who will never produce milk) are "discarded" (killed) as â€œbyproductsâ€ of the dairy industry.
.
the female calves who are not killed will become the next generation of milk producers themselves. like their mothers, they will be impregnated over and over, just to have her babies taken from her as well.
.
so the motherâ€™s heartbreak and stress of losing her baby will be repeated over and over again, until her milk production declines, at a fraction of her natural lifespan, at which time she will be sent to a violent and terrifying slaughter.
.
humans have not consumed milk past weaning or from a different species for the majority of our evolution. we absolutely do not need it for our health, we donâ€™t need it for our bones, and indeed we are much healthier avoiding it completely.
.
and, of course, there are plant-based versions of every single â€œdairyâ€ product you can think of (non-dairy milks, ice creams, cheeses, etc.).
.
please recognize the serious consequences of your food choices, and the suffering it inflicts on sentient animals. please go vegan and ditch dairy foods (and all other animal products) forever.
.

.
- well done bannon, well done breitbart, the ex-ukip leader announces in the short clip. - you helped with this. hugely.

farageâ€™s nod to steve bannon certainly hasnâ€™t aged well in the context of the recent storm around cambridge analyticaâ€™s influence over the eu referendum.

it was revealed that data from 50 million facebook profiles were looked at against the electoral register, and then used to build an algorithm which analyses peopleâ€™s personality traits in relation to their voting behaviour.

this data could then be used to find potential swing voters and create messages tailored to influence them politically.

the firmâ€™s vice president at the time was steve bannon, who was also head of the right-wing website breitbart and was running donald trumpâ€™s campaign to become us president.

monica potter claims resisting harvey weinstein seduction barred her from â€˜cider house rulesâ€™ role
##metoo #breaking news #casting #commentary #controversial #harassment #harvey weinstein #media #monica potter
actress monica potter claims that she lost a chance to appear in the 1999 film the cider house rules because she rejected harvey weinsteinâ€™s advances. speaking to her hometown cleveland television station wkyc on its letâ€™s be clear show, potter said weinstein had tried to bed her three times, â€œtwice in new york and once was in london.â€ on two occasions, weinstein made advances while wearing a bathrobe, she claimed. she rejected him physically, she said, taking advantage of his attire. â€œi belted him. i flat out belted himâ€¦ i really hit him where it hurt,â€™ she exclaimed. â€˜so yeah, i missed out on that role because of that hairy pig.â€ she added: â€œi didnâ€™t do something, so therefore i missed out on it. iâ€™m not saying the person who got it did. iâ€™m just saying i didnâ€™t.â€ the cider house rules lead female role of candy kendall was played by charlize theron in the film. potter claimed she told her father about the first weinstein incident, but did not talk about the others until her confession today. potter said she was â€œso grateful for all the women that stood upâ€ against weinstein and revealed similar confrontations. weinsteinâ€™sÂ representative told wkyc in a statement that the allegations were false, even though weinstein had great respect for the actress. â€œthe final cast decisions on cider house was the creative teamâ€™s alone. close to 100 people auditioned and it came down to two people, which is a pretty good position to be in,â€™ the representativeâ€™s statement said. â€œthere has never been anything other than respect and professionalism between weinsteinâ€™s company and ms. potter, stemming from the very thought of you in 1998, and they have only had a friendly and cordial relationship over the years, and any suggestion or allegation otherwise is simply false.â€

text:
woody allen contro amazon e amazon contro trump.
[reading time: 50 secondi] 
amazon studios Ã¨ stato accusato di aver violato il contratto stipulato con il regista woody allen su quattro film, tra cui lâ€™ultima creazione â€œrainy day in new yorkâ€, senza alcuna spiegazione lecita.
le uniche giustificazioni utilizzate dal gigante amazon contro il regista risalgono al 1990, periodo in cui woody era stato accusato di molestie dalla figlia adottiva dylan farrow, notizia recentemente riapparsa grazie allâ€™hashtag #metoo, movimento femminista che tratta della violenza sulle donne, specialmente nel settore cinematografico.
i problemi nel rapporto tra #amazon e #allen hanno iniziato a farsi sentire dal 2017, a seguito delle dimissioni dellâ€™ex presidente degli #amazonstudios, roy prince, sotto accusa anchâ€™egli per molestie, facendo cosÃ¬ slittare lâ€™uscita del nuovo film di #woody â€œrainy day in new yorkâ€, dal 2018 al 2019 a causa del passato del regista che avrebbe potuto impattare negativamente sulla produzione amazon. 
i 68 milioni di dollari che allen chiede sono per la mancanza di giustificazioni valide che, nello scorso giugno, hanno portato alla cessazione del contratto da parte del colosso, mandando in fumo tutto il lavoro e la carriera del regista, in cerca tuttora di un nuovo distributore cinematografico. 
nel frattempo, jeff bezos Ã¨ coinvolto a sua volta contro lâ€™editore e sostenitore di trump per scandalo mediatico: il â€œnational enquirerâ€ avrebbe infatti  minacciato e successivamente ricattato tramite e-mail il proprietario di amazon con foto in cui appare nudo insieme a lauren sanchez, giornalista televisiva. 
per #bezos appare inevitabile collegare questo scandalo a #trump, che da sempre lo considera un proprio rivale, â€œcome appare ovvio dai suoi tweetâ€ afferma jeff. 
pensate che queste notizie possano avere impatti negativi su amazon ? come potrebbe reagire il mercato dopo queste accuse?

text:
30 children. pure innocence came to play on thursday. from the minute they arrived magic would unfold.

one terrified little boy quivered with fear. i suggested he hug the tree he stood in front of. nature heals. and our secret enchanted garden is filled with healing.

30 children went on a journey of discovery. they wowed throughout the experience. too much magic no one ever said.

their life stories are heart breaking. they suffer in silence. until one day, as an adult, i get that email, the whatsapp. pleas for help. a story of millions of women across our city, country and continent. and the world too.

they tell me their stories. they suffer in silence. they won't write books. they have never heard of the #metoo movement. i cannot be their saviour or their comfort. i can create magic. we all need magic & miracles in our lives.

i have so much abundance in my hands. they told me to use them to heal. the golden gift. i never understood. still working it out. the gold gift box awaits delivery. it's now, or never. what's the best that can happen?

olde worlde counter of yesteryear counting modern world magic ğŸ¦„

text:
pope francis has publicly acknowledged for the first time that there is a problem of priests and even bishops sexually abusing nuns in the roman catholic church. after he was asked to comment on the issue during a news conference aboard a plane returning to rome from a trip to the united arab emirates, the pope admitted that the issue is ongoing and said that they must do more to fight the problem. in recent years, catholic nuns in india, africa, latin america, and italy have accused clerics of sexual abuse, and a vatican magazine last week mentioned nuns having abortions or giving birth to the children of priests, according to the new york times. however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.

olivia solon

text:
can we enrich masculinity? 
to where men arenâ€™t judged and labelled as weaklings for wearing their hearts on their sleeves
 to where young boys donâ€™t have to develop unhealthy coping mechanisms just because society has taught them this is what it takes to be man enough. 
to where there is less domestic violence, and more loving homes.
to where women and children donâ€™t have to deal with unnecessary trauma.
to where men are brave enough to stand up for women and their rights.
to where promises arenâ€™t for fooling.
to where women donâ€™t succumb to sexual harassment just to keep their jobs.
to where emotions, which are a god-given charm, do not impose any danger to masculinity, nor the definition of strength.
to where there are insightful social norms and constructs.
redefining masculinity is nowhere equal to omitting it. 
now can we? 
embrace humanity, compassion and empathy

notice 1: this article does not, in any way, disclaim any abhorrent and despicable acts done by women.

text:
this week on @popcultureconfidential: â€˜r kelly/bryan singer/michael jackson/weinstein, shocking exposÃ©s and survivors getting heard!â€™ i am joined by rachel leah writer at salon.com covering culture, race and criminal justice.

we talk about the shocking wave of articles, exposÃ©s and documentaries about allegations of sexual misconduct by high profile artists and industry titans. allegations that have dogged them for years, sometimes even for decades. how can it be possible that these allegations have been industry, and even public, knowledge for years and still their careers flourish? but has the #metoo movement allowed for more survivors to come forward with their stories when the justice system seems to often have failed them?  rachel leah has been covering these topics extensively and joins us this week for an in-depth conversation.

words for the world:
me too part 9.
a series. .
.
.
passion and violence
i want to feel alive
so much so
i have a death wish. .
.
.
i know not to 
trust you
yet you know how 
to trigger each 
of my fears.
i feel controlled 
by you - it thrills me
you might kill me 
if i try to get away. 
i know
i might do it anyway
if i feel alone again. 
and each and every
morning it is the same
you force your way 
on top of me
telling me i want it,
but i know you 
get off by them hearing,
you love to
disgrace me, 
so its even worse.
no one wants 
a used up whore. -mahriyah willow

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

.

text:
former u.s. national security adviser michael flynn admitted on friday that he asked russia to delay a u.n. vote seen as damaging to israel, but diplomats said it was not the only country he and presidential adviser jared kushner lobbied.

in the hours before the vote by the 15-member united nations security council on dec. 23, flynn also phoned the u.n. missions of uruguay and malaysia, and kushner spoke with kim darroch, the british ambassador to the united states, according to diplomats familiar with the conversations, who spoke on condition of anonymity.

the lobbying took place before republican president donald trump, who was known for his pro-israel campaign rhetoric, took office on jan. 20. it failed, with the security council adopting a resolution demanding an end to israeli settlement building on land palestinians want for an independent state. the vote was 14 in favor and one abstention by the united states.

the efforts made on israel's behalf capped several days of unusual diplomacy. in a surprise dec. 21 move, egypt had called for a vote the next day on the draft resolution, prompting both trump and israel to urge washington to veto the text.

a senior israeli official told reuters that israeli officials contacted trump's transition team at a "high level" to ask for help after failing to persuade democratic president barack obama's administration to veto the draft u.n. resolution.

according to court documents made public on friday, a member of trump's presidential transition team, later identified by sources as trump's son-in-law kushner, told flynn on dec. 22 to contact officials from foreign governments, including russia, to convince them to delay the vote or veto the resolution.

flynn spoke with then-russian ambassador to the united states sergei kislyak that day, and again the following day, according to the court documents.

michelle nichols
reuters

text:
wylie, who worked for scl, the british-based parent of cambridge analytica, told the senate judiciary committee that cambridge analytica hired hackers to collect data it then used against opponents of its political clients.

allegations of the improper use of data for 87 million facebook users by cambridge analytica, which was hired by trump's 2016 election campaign, have led to investigations in the united states and europe.

bannon worked on trump's campaign and became a white house aide when trump took office in january 2017. bannon left in august 2017.

wylie, who has provided reports about how the firm used data facebook collected, on wednesday described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election.
.
- one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters, wylie said. - the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like 'drain the swamp' or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the 'deep state' that weren't necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement, wylie said.

another witness who testified to the judiciary committee, tufts university associate professor eitan hersh, said he was "skeptical" of the effectiveness that such political messaging and targeting. - no person is persuadable all the time, he said.

mark hosenball
reuters

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
throughout the committee hearing, several republican senators including ted cruz and thom tillis pointed to the obama campaignâ€™s use of facebook data, to highlight the fact that such practices are bipartisan.

however, people who downloaded the obama campaign app were aware they were using a political app. by contrast, the data obtained by cambridge analytica was obtained via a personality quiz application whose users had no idea their data would be used by a political campaign.

cambridge analytica improperly obtained the personal information of millions of facebook users to build profiles of us voters in order to target them with personalised political advertisements, via a related uk-based entity called scl elections.
.
- we exploited facebook to harvest millions of peopleâ€™s profiles, said wylie in march. - and built models to exploit what we knew about them and target their inner demons. that was the basis the entire company was built on.

wylie has previously told mps at a british select committee that the eu referendum was won through fraud after vote leave allegedly used a network of companies to get round election spending laws. he said he thought there â€œcould have been a different outcome had there not been, in my view, cheatingâ€. he also met privately with house democrats in april, but wednesdayâ€™s hearing was his first public appearance before us lawmakers.

olivia solon
the guardian

text:
discussing the #yogasutras in our #yogateachertraining seems to get more interesting every year. 
the concept of #bramacharya (â€œchastityâ€ in the more conservative readings, â€œintegrity in sexual relationshipsâ€ in the liberal ones) is always...a topic of strong interest for people. 
most especially now, in the wake of #metoo , i canâ€™t get through the lecture without wanting to scream: â€œsex is not the problem! itâ€™s not even the issue!â€ because, in the world and time weâ€™re living in, sex is not the issue. the unspoken abuse of power is the issue. 
in my experience, the healthiest perspectives on sexuality do not come from clergy (#duh) or from philosophers. they come from those whose experience of sexuality has been commingled with marginalization or violenceâ€”and who have as a result *insisted* on something better. 
so i canâ€™t give this lecture without thinking of the beautiful souls who lived and died in the depths of the aids crisis, who gave us the tools to stay healthy through their own dogged, our-lives-depend-on-this researchâ€”when our government was happy to just let folks die. 
i canâ€™t give this lecture without thinking of the leather community, who forged a way to talk about power dynamics and sexuality with consciousness and consent at the forefront. 
i canâ€™t talk about this stuff without also thinking of the horrendous effects that sesta/fosta has had on sex workers, and how state-approved violence has always been leveled as a threat against any woman who dared to assume her body belonged to her alone. 
itâ€™s a lot. but #philosophy is only meaningful when itâ€™s #alive.

text:
there's about a 6 year difference between these two pictures. i've always (and i mean always) struggles with my weight. i was always the bigger girl, the fat girl. i was bullied all through school. i became depressed and suicidal. it didn't matter how hard i was working towards my goal, it was never enough for  everyone around me. i would try and stay as active as possible, but get discouraged every time i'd have someone watching me. i always felt like i was never enough, or i would never be good enough for anyone. i hit a rough patch in my life. i stumbled into an abusive relationship (mentally, physically and emotionally). i was raped. i lost a ton of weight in a short period of time. but i wasn't happy. i lost the weight due to the situations that happened. once that relationship ended i gained a lot of it back. that was 5 years ago. in the last year i got more active, got my life back on track, started caring more about my mental health and doing what's right for me. i'm finally in a happy place, and excited to start this journey again, with a happy and healthy mind.

there's about a 6 year difference between these two pictures. i have always (and i mean always) struggles with my weight. i was always the bigger girl, the fat girl. i was bullied all through school. i became depressed and suicidal. it didn't matter how hard i was working towards my goal, it was never enough for  everyone around me. i would try and stay as active as possible, but get discouraged every time i'd have someone watching me. i always felt like i was never enough, or i would never be good enough for anyone. i hit a rough patch in my life. i stumbled into an abusive relationship (mentally, physically and emotionally). i was raped. i lost a ton of weight in a sho period of time. but i wasn't happy. i lost the weight due to the situations that happened. once that relationship ended i gained a lot of it back. that was 5 years ago. in the last year i got more active, got my life back on track, staed caring more about my mental health and doing what's right for me. i am finally in a happy place, and excited to sta this journey again, with a happy and healthy mind.

text: hey! the following is a rant. so if arenâ€™t interested in reading what an educated, pissed off woman thinks about the grammies, about the music industry, or about the #metoo movement, youâ€™re welcome to look at my abs in this picture or to just leave this post entirely. i actually did a lot of sit-ups. and â€œnoâ€, i really donâ€™t think iâ€™m â€œall that.â€ donâ€™t worry. | there are very good reasons that womenâ€™s voices are missing from popular music, from stages, and from screens. and itâ€™s because we have been systematically silenced and excluded. a lot of people asked why i stopped performing. and itâ€™s because one psycho ruined it for me. i donâ€™t feel safe performing. cyber stalking often leads to real life stalking. and you know what? being stalked isnâ€™t fun. you can block a psycho on every social media, on your phone, on your email...and if he knows enough about you and is a little tech savvy, heâ€™ll find a way to keep bothering you. this piece of shit even harassed my mom. i hope he rots in hell. my experience isnâ€™t unique. itâ€™s common. and it drives a lot of women to take more powerful roles as creators, in business and art. there will be a day when men like the piece of shit that has made my life a living hell will think a few more times before fucking with a woman. i wrote a lot of angry songs for a while.  and i really am glad that i did. it gave me the courage to move beyond my rage and into a place of health and wellness. no one will ever fuck with me again. thatâ€™s for sure. i can sell that kind of dirtbag twenty miles away. ladies, let me know if you need any help identifying the stench of a goodfornothing. #metoo #fuckoff also, iâ€™ve put on a solid 10 pounds of muscle since then and have learned to a) punch b) kick above my head. whatever. iâ€™m feeling like a boss today. and i donâ€™t mind sharing it, just in case you need a reminder that youâ€™re a boss too, queens. #feminism #newyear #fitfam

ğŸŒº we welcome presenter tania loveheart, to the 2019 retreat - tania is deeply inspired by life to hold space for others to offer people opportunities for self-development and self-empowerment. it has been through her own learnings as life that she believes unwaveringly in the power of self-affirming thought, belief and action that moves mountains and parts the seas.
âœ¨
her discussion workshop atÂ is about creative expression : honouring the freedom of emotional expression. âœ¨
tania says â€¦â€i believe each and every one of us is called at some point of recognition to honour the self in light of emotional freedom.
âœ¨
as a human being, you have the capacity to express yourself through the gift of emotional sense. for many, however, these emotional senses are a hindrance to their wellbeing. we've been taught to suppress our emotions and hence they become underdeveloped. âœ¨
opening up to the wonder and the freedom to express emotionally not only develops your capacity to unburden emotional suffering but also allows the self the freedom to live life fully in honour of the self.â€

repost from @bitchmedia - âœ¨adventures in feministory: fannie lou hamer âœ¨â €
.â €
fannie lou hamer, like many women activists of the american civil rights movement, is often overlooked despite her staggering contributions to social change. â €
.â €
in 1962, hamer attended a meeting of the student nonviolent coordinating committee (sncc), and instantly became interested in civil rights, specifically voting rights. numerous challenges were set up to keep black people from voting in mississippi, including written tests and poll taxes. she immediately made efforts to register to vote and of course immediately faced police brutality, racist harassment, and unemployment. hamer eventually did register to vote, and also became a sncc field secretary.â €
.â €
fannie lou hamer was a founding member of mississippi freedom democratic party, which was formed to challenge the all-white, anti-civil rights mississippi democratic delegation sent to the 1964 national convention. in addition to this, hamer also began a day-care center in her hometown of ruleville, was part of the delta ministry, a community-organizing and support network, raised money for low-income housing, was on the board of a garment plant designed for more jobs, and even ran for u.s. congress in 1965 with two other women.â €
.â €
âœ¨adventures in feministory is a series highlighting the important and often overlooked contributions of women throughout history. in honor of #blackhistorymonth, we are spotlighting black women who have made waves, enacted social change, and left a lasting impact for future generations to come. âœ¨
.

text: what a wonderful and empowering day this has been for me! getting to listen to these strong, powerful, resilient, and passionate women leaderâ€™s (the list can go on and on) today has been one of the greatest learning experiences for me. understanding that being my authentic self will generate success, how to discover and utilize my strengths to accomplish my goals, discussing equal rights for all women, grasping the concept of intersectionality, and understanding the downfalls of white feminism are only some of the key points i took away from the conference. all of the keynote speakers and panelist were so excellent! like melissa abad, ph.d. who is a sociologist at the stanford vmware womenâ€™s leadership innovation lab and leads the women intersectional leadership research agenda. or @monica.stockhausen who became a professor at the age of only 24 and now owns her own company nerdy girls rock! which is designed to professionally develop ie women in the collegiate and professional market. and finally the presidents of the national womenâ€™s march @tamikadmallory @bobblandofficial! not gonna lie i fan-girlâ€™d when i saw tamika mallory! i mean cmon a woman who worked closely with the obama admin. as an advocate for civil rights issues?! or bob bland speaking about the #metoo movement and opening my eyes to understanding my attack mattered and i am not to blame regardless of circumstances. and i should not be ashamed or afraid to tell my story. these women are definitely role models and people i look up too. so it was an honor getting to be here today and learn from these amazing women! looking forward to the next womenâ€™s leadership conference! â¤ï¸ğŸ’ª thank you #csusb! #csusbwomensleadershipconference #activatetomotivate #womensleadership #tamikamallory #bobbland #survivor #inspire #motivate #empower #womensupportingwomen

text:
day 5, awareness week. unfortunately this is how i met @missangeline00. just randomly following each other on instagram i came across her post from the hospital letting everyone know she was ok. i almost didn't reach out. i was afraid she would think i was insane. but she hopped right on board with the idea.

this photo had to stay unreleased until now for reasons beyond our control. until now. this is bravery, this is strength. this is a model who stepped back in front of a camera less than a week after getting beat up by her (ex)boyfriend to say "this shit needs to stop now!" who's with us?

text:
hosting my second galentineâ€™s of the month and had to make this fruit cookie pizza because it was such a hit so i had to share it with yâ€™all! i subbed the lemon juice with a few drops lemon oil and everyone couldnâ€™t get enough! â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
ingredients:
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
crust:
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
1/4 cup butter, softened
1/2 cup sugar
1 egg
1/2 tsp. vanilla
1 1/4 cups flour
1/4 tsp. baking powder
1/4 tsp. baking soda
1/4 tsp. salt
filling:
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
4 oz. cream cheese, softened
1/4 cup powdered sugar
1 cup whipped topping (i used cool whip)
fruit topping:
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
i used raspberries, blueberries, and blackberries, but you can use whatever types of fruit you like.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
glaze:
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
1/4 cup sugar
2 tsp. cornstarch
1/4 cup water
1/8 cup lemon juice
for crust: cream butter and sugar together. add in egg and vanilla, mix. add flour baking powder, baking soda, and salt, mix. press dough into heart shape onto a greased cookie sheet. bake at 350 degrees for 12-15 minutes or until golden brown. cool completely.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
for glaze: mix sugar, cornstarch, water, and lemon juice in a small saucepan. bring to a boil over medium heat and then boil for a couple of minutes until thickened. cool for about 30 minutes.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
for filling: beat cream cheese and powdered sugar. add whipped topping and mix well.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
now put it all together! spread filling onto cookie crust. add your desired fruit. then drizzle the glaze over the top. store finished valentine fruit pizza in the refrigerator.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
- this was steve bannon's baby, said former contractor christopher wylie, who described cambridge analytica as "bannon's arsenal of weaponry to wage a culture war on america using military strategies."
.
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
95.5% of prisoners in the uk are men. men are more likely than women to be arrested by police for doing the same crime. men are more likely to be prosecuted by the cps than women for doing the same crime. men are more likely to be given a jail sentence by the courts than women for doing the same crime. men are more likely to serve a longer sentence with the prison service than women for doing the same crime.... so the bbc runs 3 articles about female prisoners!

partially the discrimination against men is subconscious, given that women are always portrayed to be the victim, and partially it's by design. here's a female green party leader saying it is right for women to be punished less for the same crime because punishing women affects their families... the insinuation being that punishing men doesn't break up families. punishment should be based on the crime, not what gender, race, or anything else the person was born!

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
two more weeks before i end chapter 12 of book 39 in my life story. much has come my way over the last year that may have been meant to break me. but, here i am unbroken and joy filled. this last year has also brought a lot of wonderful times and happy memories. and, so again i say here i am unbroken and joyfilled.
i am happy, because i choose to be happy within myself first.
i am loved, because i choose to love myself first before expecting someone else to. 
not everyone who pretends to care really does, and that is ok. not everyone, who claims they'd be there for me was, and that's ok. not everyone who says they miss me when i run into them ever checked on me, and that's ok. not everyone is honest, and that's ok. 
i have distanced myself from a lot of people, because my mental well-being is important. i've decided i don't want to start my next book off celebrating with people who have not been genuinely there for me. so, no celebrations with a lot of people. i will celebrate with those i choose and prefer no one attempts to choose for me. it's my choice, and i truly hope people can and will respect my decision.

text:
hannah gadsby has a thing or two to say about picasso
pen and ink and watercolor pencil on bristol 
11 x 14
part of the misunderstood women series 
just don't miss hannah gadsby's 'nanette' on netflix.  i'm not sure it's correct to call it comedy. i do think it's an important social document. and it's funny.  and it's heartbreaking. 
she talks about what i began to suspect when i saw the picasso sculpture exhibition at moma and noticed all the sculpted  women had clenched fists.  then there's the painting of the woman with a fish on her head.  the editor of the book i read thought maybe it was a commentary on the scarcity of food during the war. i imagine rather that perhaps the model complained about her hat so he punished her by putting a fish on her head.

hannah was the easiest to draw in this series so far; she's a very clear communicator. .
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
do klaus nomi and julie andrews come to you in dreams?
.
.
++++++++
.
.
it's 1981.

text_retweet:
for your knowledge 
reposted from @harrieteve9 -  richmond, virginia â€” the political crisis in virginia exploded wednesday when the state's attorney general confessed to putting on blackface in the 1980s and a woman went public with detailed allegations of sexual assault against the lieutenant governor. with gov. ralph northam's career already hanging by a thread over a racist photo in his 1984 medical school yearbook, the day's developments threatened to take down all three of virginia's top elected officials, all of them democrats.

the twin developments began with attorney general mark herring issuing a statement saying he wore brown makeup and a wig in 1980 to look like a rapper during a party as a 19-year-old student at the university of virginia. herring â€” who has been among those calling on northam to resign â€” said he was "deeply, deeply sorry for the pain that i cause with this revelation." he said that in the days ahead, "honest conversations and discussions will make it clear whether i can or should continue to serve as attorney general." then, within hours, vanessa tyson, the woman whose sexual assault allegations against lt. gov. justin fairfax governor surfaced earlier this week, issued a detailed statement saying fairfax forced her to perform oral sex on him in 2004 during the democratic national convention in boston.

tyson, a 42-year-old political scientist who is on a fellowship at stanford university and specializes in the political discourse of sexual assault, said, "i have no political motive. i am a proud democrat." "mr. fairfax has tried to brand me as a liar to a national audience, in service to his political ambitions, and has threatened litigation," she said. "given his false assertions, i'm compelled to make clear what happened." the associated press typically does not identify those who say they were sexually assaulted, but tyson issued the statement in her name. fairfax â€” who is in line to become governor if northam resigns â€” has repeatedly denied her allegations, saying that the encounter was consensual and that he is the victim of a strategically timed political smear. {swipeâ—€ï¸} source: ap
#metoo #virginia

whether hater or supporter, contributor or reporter, you are jttots.

text:
check out my most recent article (link in bio) for the good, the bad, and a real solution to the backlash
--
from recent @bloomberg and @nytimes articles, to tiffany dufu's @tdufu @msnbc interview (shared earlier this week and available @dralessandrawall), to an email i just received from my sons' school - subject title: "raising kids in the #metoo era" - it looks like the #metoo movement continues to gain traction, and that's a good thing... or is it?â €
--â €
on the one hand, it's heartening to see we're still talking about harassment, appropriate behavior and the importance of speaking up even when you feel all alone; movements like these tend to come and go like shoe trends.â €
--â €
on the other hand, an all too predictable reactive backlash doesn't bode well for male-female relationships in the workplace.â €
--â €
read the full article: "trust in the workplace in the #metoo era" via the link up top (@dralessandrawall). let me know your thoughts in the comments: is the #metoo movement a good thing?â €
.â €
.â €

text:
â€œi donâ€™t know about ghosts,â€ she was saying; â€œbut i do know that our souls can be made to go outside our bodies when we are alive. ... a very easy way to feel â€˜em go is to lie on the grass at night and look straight up at some big bright star; and by fixing your mind upon it, you will soon find that you are hundreds and hundreds oâ€™ miles away from your body, which you donâ€™t even seem to want at all.â€
-tess
â€¢
before my husband and i officially started dating, we picked out favorite books for each other to read. i made my yet-to-be boyfriend read this book, tess of the dâ€™urbervilles, which in retrospect was an interesting choice to give a boy i really liked, because the major theme of this whole book is basically that men suck. i guess he didnâ€™t read too much into it, because obviously things worked out between us (i mean, i found a guy who was willing to read classic lit for fun and could talk to me about intelligently, clearly i fell head over heels for him. also clearly, heâ€™s way better than angel clare.)
â€¢
i just reread this again for my virtual book club, and what an interesting read in the era of #metoo. hardy was a feminist before feminism was a thing.
â€¢
normally, i donâ€™t go in for super depressing books (which is why i pretty much hate modern literary fiction), but for some reason, i love tess with all my heart. maybe i see a lot of myself in her (her personality, not her experience thank goodness). whatever it is, i highly recommend this book. despite the tragic beginning, despite the tragic ending, despite the fact all the men are terrible, it is a beautiful read.
â€¢

text:
rp @meat_your_future 
the miracle of life is torture for dairy cows, as their babies are taken from them again and again.
.
like any mammal, cows only produce milk for their calves, after they delivered a baby calf. but because we want their milk, we forcibly impregnate them over and over, to get and keep them lactating, and take their calves away after they are born.  this obviously causes intense distress for both the mother and her baby.
.
the surplus calves (including all of the males who will never produce milk) are "discarded" (killed) as â€œbyproductsâ€ of the dairy industry.
.
the female calves who are not killed will become the next generation of milk producers themselves. like their mothers, they will be impregnated over and over, just to have her babies taken from her as well.
.
so the motherâ€™s heartbreak and stress of losing her baby will be repeated over and over again, until her milk production declines, at a fraction of her natural lifespan, at which time she will be sent to a violent and terrifying slaughter.
.
humans have not consumed milk past weaning or from a different species for the majority of our evolution. we absolutely do not need it for our health, we donâ€™t need it for our bones, and indeed we are much healthier avoiding it completely.
.
and, of course, there are plant-based versions of every single â€œdairyâ€ product you can think of (non-dairy milks, ice creams, cheeses, etc.).
.
please recognize the serious consequences of your food choices, and the suffering it inflicts on sentient animals. please go vegan and ditch dairy foods (and all other animal products) forever.
.

text:
i gave a talk at @makerswomen yesterday about financial literacy and what comes after #timesup and #metoo for us. for me its #ialso
years ago when i started down this path i did not understand what a #fuckyounumber was. a fuck you number is a term that i was introduced to by my guy friends. it is a number past retirement, that entitles you to only do the things you chose. 
every guy i know can tell me his #fuckyou number but women become paralyzed with this question. we as women need to get beyond networking and get into "net worthing". when i was younger, good lawyers, wealth managers, bankers and investors were limited and i did not understand all the dynamics of capital, liquidation preferences, strike prices, cap tables, options, and complicated deal structures. 
men know these things because they talk about it. making money is a function of friendship for men but its not for women. that has to change. 
every day women get hazedÂ Â not because we are getting inducted into, but for simply wanting to be in the paid club. 
making money is an essential part of equality and we need to get focused on that. while we have benefited from a pr halo in a post #metoo and #timesup world, it has yet to create a wealth movement for us. 
so for me after #metoo and #timesup its #ialso
i also want generational wealth, investments and opportunity
i also want the opportunity to fail and try again
i also want to be shame free, entitled to my place in the world as the leader i want to be. #ialso link in bio ğŸ§µ@tiffthestylist

text:
breaking news
.
.
.
a second woman has come forward accusing virginia lieutenant governor justin fairfax of sexual assault.

in a letter from her lawyer, meredith watson claims she was raped by fairfax in 2000, when they were both students at duke university. 
the letter characterizes the alleged attack as â€œpremeditated and aggressive.â€ the two were friends but never dated or had any romantic relationship,â€ the letter says. â€œms. watson shared her account of the rape with friends in a series of emails and facebook messages that are now in our possession,â€ the letter continues. â€œadditionally, we have statements from former classmates corroborating that ms. watson immediately told friends that mr. fairfax had raped her.â€ the letter adds that watson was â€œupsetâ€ after another woman, dr. vanessa tyson, came forward with her own accusations of sexual assault against fairfax earlier this week.

text:
the hardest thing i've been struggling my whole life is to let go of the past.

when i was younger i was raped and molested by my step father for 7 years. my childhood was taken from me. i had the mind set that, "my brother and sister have to be alright", i fed them, protected them. i made sure they never had to endure what i went through. after a neighbor had stumbled into his bedroom one morning and had saw me, a naked 11 year old sleeping in the bed with her stepfather who was in his underwear. 3 days later, i was moving to california to be with my mom... but he stayed behind, when i had the courage to say something to the police, less than a year and half later, the statue of limitations had gone into affect and there's nothing anyone can do. i have severe ptsd and i struggle more than anybody would understand just by looking at me.. i'm stronger than my past. i'm a person who will do anything for everyone me because i know what it's like to be alone. i know what it's like to hit rock bottom. i know what it's like to feel like bruised fruit. and to feel like your just damaged goods that no one could ever possibly love. but i also know you're wrong. you're relient. you're strength. you're the meaning of beauty in this world, because you are still here, proving that they didn't win..
